tool.name: SupplementaryContoursFull

param.name: out_features
param.dialogReference:
Output line feature class containing regular, index and supplementary contours.

Resulting contour types (regular, index, supplementary) are stored in Type field. Filtered out supplementary contours are flagged with 0 in Show field. All other contours are flagged with 1 in Show field

param.name: cell_size
param.dialogReference: Cell size used for generation of region width and centrality rasters. It can be selected freely, without any dependency on the input raster DEM cell size. The smaller the cell size, the more precise width and centrality estimation. However, extremely small values may cause long computation time. Set reasonably.

param.name: contour_interval
param.dialogReference:
Regular contour interval. Supplementary contours will be generated at the half of this interval. For example, if the contour interval is set to 5 elevation units (meters, feet) and the base contour level is 0, then supplementary contours will be generated at height levels equal to 2.5, 7.5, 12.5 elevation units and so on.

Resulting contour elevations are stored in Contour field.

For topographic mapping purposes it is recommended to select a regular contour interval on which 100 could be divided without a remainder. Therefore, 1, 2, 2.5, 5, 10, 20, 25, 50 and 100 units are good choices, while 3, 4, 15, 30 and 40 units are discouraged.

param.name: base_contour
param.dialogReference:
Base contour level determines the anchor point of an arithmetic progression of regular contours' elevation levels. In most of the situations it is recommended to set base contour level equal to zero. However, if base contour level is set to 2 elevation units (meters, feet) and contour interval is 3 units, then regular contours will be generated at elevations equal to 2, 5, 8 units and so on.

Default value is 0.

param.name: index_contour
param.dialogReference:
Index contours are thicker contour lines, which are used to facilitate visual interpretation of contoured terrain. Usually each 4th, 5th or 10th contour is marked as index contour.

Default value is 5. Resulting flag (index) is stored in Type field.

For topographic mapping purposes it is recommended to select index contour step such that 100 or 1000 can be divided on the resulting index contour interval without a remainder. Therefore, if regular contour interval is 20 elevation units (meters, feet) then each 5th should be indexed, while for 25 units each 4th should be indexed. Indexing each 10th is usually applied in large scales, where the regular contour interval is equal to small value like 0.5 or 1 elevation units.

param.name: closed_width_avg
param.dialogReference:
Average region width of a closed supplementary contour should be equal or larger than this value.

Default value is 0.125 of maximum region width.

param.name: width_min
param.dialogReference:
Supplementary contours are prohibited in regions with width smaller than this value.

Default value is 0.25 of maximum region width.

param.name: width
param.dialogReference:
Supplementary contours are placed inside regions smaller than this value, but larger than Region width (minimal), only if their centrality is smaller than linearly interpolated value between Centrality (minimal) and Centrality (optimal).

Default value is 0.5 of maximum region width.

param.name: width_max
param.dialogReference:
Supplementary contours are placed inside regions smaller than this value, but larger than Region width (optinal), only if their centrality is smaller than linearly interpolated value between Centrality (optimal) and 1.

Default value is 0.75 of maximum region width.

param.name: centrality_min
param.dialogReference:
The maximum allowable centrality for regions, which width is equal to Region width (minimal) parameter. For regions with width between Region width (minimal) and Region width (optimal) the maximum allowable centrality is linearly interpolated between Centrality (minimal) and Centrality (optimal).

Default value is 0.4.

param.name: centrality
param.dialogReference:
The maximum allowable centrality for regions, which width is equal to Region width (optimal) parameter. For regions with width between Region width (optimal) and Region width (maximal) the maximum allowable centrality is linearly interpolated between Centrality (optimal) and 1.

Default value is 0.8.

param.name: centrality_ext
param.dialogReference:
Minimal value of supplementary contour centrality which must be reached during extension.

Default value is 0.8.

param.name: min_gap
param.dialogReference:
Maximal allowable length of a gap between supplementary contour segments. If a gap is smaller, then it is filled, and the adjacent supplementary contour sections are merged into one.

Default value is 1.0 of Region width (optimal)

param.name: min_len
param.dialogReference:
Minimal allowable length of a supplementary contour segment. If a segment is smaller, then it is removed.

Default value is 1.0 of Region width (optimal)

param.name: ext_len
param.dialogReference:
The distance on which supplementary contours are extended from both ends to reach approximately central position. The most central point of the traced path is selected, and if its centrality is equal or larger than Centrality (extension), then supplementary contour is extended in that direction until that point.

Default value is 1.0 of Region width (optimal).

param.name: extend
param.dialogReference:
Extend supplementary contours until largest centrality equal or greater than Centrality (extension), but no longer than Extension length.

Default value is True.

param.name: absolute
param.displayname: Set width and length parameters in projection units (absolute values)
param.dialogReference:
Width and length parameters of this tool are set in relative values by default. Widths are expressed as fractions of the maximum region width for the selected contour interval. Lengths are expressed as fractions of Region width (optimal) parameter. This proved to be very convenient for experimental processing of diverse elevation models with different spatial extent and contour interval (otherwise you need to adjust the parameters for each model).

If you need to set the exact values of these parameters in projection units, then check this box. For example, it is reasonable for sheet-based topographic map production, where the parameterization must be standardized and should not depend on the properties of each sheet's terrain.

Default value is False.

param.name: mode
param.dialogReference:
The mode used for computation of region width raster:

  • CPP - fast external compiled C++ module.

  • PYTHON - straight Python implementation of the same algorithm. Much slower than CPP version.

Default value is CPP. If loading of external module fails, then only PYTHON option will be available.

tool.summary:
This tool is used to generate a full set of contours, including regular, index and supplementary. The processing includes the following steps:

  1. Extraction of regular and supplementary contours.

  2. Subdivision of the area into the set of regions bordered by regular contours and the boundary of interpolation area.

  3. Calculation of region width and centrality rasters.

  4. Filtering of supplementary contours' vertices based on width and centrality criteria.

  5. Short gap filling, small segment removal and extension of supplementary contour segments.

  6. Filtering of closed supplementary contours based on length and average width criteria.

  7. Merging the results and flagging of index contours

For the short version of the tool which uses precomputed width and centrality rasters see Supplementary contours.

A detailed description of the method can be found in the following paper:

Samsonov T., Koshel S, Walther D., Jenny B. Automated placement of supplementary contour lines // International Journal of Geographical Information Science. — 2019. — Vol. 33. — DOI: 10.1080/13658816.2019.1610965
